\#\#\# \*\*Expected GPT Response Format:\*\*  
\`\`\`  
Team Efficiency & Scale

At 65 FTE generating $1.2M monthly AGI, you're producing $18,462 per person. This positions you solidly in the healthy efficiency range, above the $15K threshold that separates sustainable agencies from those struggling with team productivity. Your efficiency suggests good pricing discipline and reasonable productivity levels for an agency at your scale.

Operational Leverage

Your 4:1 billable-to-support ratio (52 delivery staff, 13 operations/leadership) indicates very lean operational leverage. You're operating efficiently with minimal overhead, though this ratio suggests you may be near the threshold where additional support infrastructure could enhance delivery team productivity. This lean structure is typical for agencies prioritizing efficiency over extensive management layers.

Delivery Model Complexity

Your "mostly specialists" structure with dedicated roles (strategists, creatives, media buyers, account managers) creates moderate coordination complexity. With 3-4 management layers and formal leadership roles like Head of Delivery and Creative Director present, you've built infrastructure to orchestrate specialist collaboration. This structure aligns with the complexity required to serve mid-market clients — simpler clients wouldn't justify specialist overhead, while your current scale supports role specialization.

Founder Involvement

You're spending time on a "mix of client work and operations," indicating you're in the transition phase between being the primary deliverer and orchestrating delivery through others. With leadership infrastructure present (Head of Delivery, Creative Director, Account Director), the delegation framework exists, though you haven't fully transitioned out of client work. This is a common inflection point at your scale where completing the shift to "mostly operations" or "mostly strategy" unlocks further growth capacity.

Capacity Dynamics

Your 70-80% utilization indicates the team is well-utilized with some headroom. Combined with 13% contractor workforce, you have flexibility to scale through a mix of contractor expansion and selective hiring. This balanced capacity position suggests you're not maxed out but operating at healthy productivity levels.  
